content.text:
### Animate While In View (Target)

Source: https://motion.dev/docs/react-motion-component

Sets a target animation state that the element should animate to when it enters the viewport. This is useful for scroll-triggered animations.

```jsx
// As target
<motion.div whileInView={{ opacity: 1 }} />
```

--------------------------------

### Gesture Animation Shortcuts (Vue)

Source: https://motion.dev/docs/vue-animation

Provides shortcut props for animating elements based on user gestures like hover, press, and focus. These props allow for quick setup of interactive animations without explicit event handling. `whileInView` animates when the element enters the viewport.

```html
<motion.button
  :initial="{ opacity: 0 }"
  :whileHover="{ backgroundColor: 'rgba(220, 220, 220, 1)' }"
  :whilePress="{ backgroundColor: 'rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)' }"
  :whileInView="{ opacity: 1 }"
/>
```

--------------------------------

### Scroll-Triggered Animations with useAnimate and useInView

Source: https://motion.dev/docs/react-use-animate

Combines useAnimate with useInView to create animations that trigger when the component's scope scrolls into the viewport. The animation plays only when the element is visible.

```jsx
import { useAnimate, useInView } from "motion/react"
import { useEffect } from "react"

function Component() {
  const [scope, animate] = useAnimate()
  const isInView = useInView(scope)

  useEffect(() => {
     if (isInView) {
       animate(scope.current, { opacity: 1 })
     }
  }, [isInView])

  return (
    <ul ref={scope}>
      <li />
      <li />
      <li />
    </ul>
  )
}
```

--------------------------------

### Detect Element Visibility with inView (JavaScript)

Source: https://motion.dev/docs/inview

The inView function detects when elements enter and leave the viewport. It's built on the Intersection Observer API for performance. Callbacks can be provided to execute actions when visibility changes.

```javascript
import { inView } from "motion"

inView("#carousel li", (element) => {
  animate(element, { opacity: 1 })
})
```

```javascript
// Selector
inView("section", callback)

// Element
const box = document.getElementById("box")
inView(box, callback)
```

```javascript
inView(element, () => {
  console.log("Element has entered the viewport")
})
```

```javascript
inView("a", (element, info) => {
  console.log("The link ", element, " has entered the viewport")
})
```

```javascript
inView(element,
  (element, enterInfo) => {
    const animation = animate(element, { opacity: 1 })

    // This will fire when the element leaves the viewport
    return (leaveInfo) => animation.stop()
  }
)
```

```javascript
const carousel = document.querySelector("#carousel")

inView("#carousel li", callback, { root: carousel })
```

```javascript
const stop = inView(element, callback)

stop()
```

### inView

Source: https://motion.dev/docs/inview

`inView` detects when elements enter and leave the viewport. Detecting when an element is in view can help creating effects like animating elements when they scroll into and out of view, deactivating animations when they're no longer visible, lazy-loading content, and automatically starting/stopping videos. The `inView` function is built on the browser's native Intersection Observer API for the best possible performance and a tiny filesize.

